Decimal Floating-Point (DFP) Benchmarks

For more details, please refer to the following papers:

      Wang, Tsen, Jhalani, Schulte  "Benchmarks and Performance Analysis
      of Decimal Floating-Point Applications" from IEEE International
      Conference on Computer Design, Oct 2007.

      Anderson, Tsen, Wang, Compton, Schulte "Performance Analysis of Decimal
      Floating-Point Libraries and Its Impact on Decimal Hardware and Software
      Solutions" from IEEE International Conference on Computer Design, 
      Oct 2009.

Commercial benchmarks have been created to measure the performance benefits of 
various decimal floating point implementations. Our benchmark suite includes 
the following applications:

    * Banking
    * Tax Solver
    * Telco
    * Risk Management
    * Currency Conversion

-- Libraries

The benchmarks require support for DFP in an underlying module.  Currently the
benchmarks are compatible with three underlying modules.  To run the benchmarks
using decimal floating-point types, please download one of the three supported
dfp modules:

   * IBM DecNumber: 			
        http://www.alphaworks.ibm.com/tech/decnumber
        Should be compiled to files named 'LINUXDecNum.a' and 
        'LINUXDecFloats.a', then either copied or linked in each benchmark's 
        directory. We have included a Makefile that should compile the
        library correctly. 

        See $BENCHMARK_ROOT/decNumberLib/README for more information.
        

   * Intel Decimal Floating-Point Math: 
        http://softwareblogs.intel.com/2008/03/06/intel-decimal-floating-point-math-library/
        Should be compiled to a file called 'libbid.a' and either copied 
        or linked in each benchmark's directory. We have included a script
        called make_for_benchmarks.sh that should compile this library
        with the correct parameters.

	See $BENCHMARK_ROOT/IntelRDFPMathLib1.0/README for more information


   * GCC 4.3 or above: 			
        http://gcc.gnu.org/
        Gcc should be compiled with decimal floating-point enabled.

Note: It is also possible to run the benchmarks with binary floating-point (BFP)
support.  This does not require downloading any modules, however the benchmarks are
intended DFP rather than for BFP.

-- Compiling the Benchmarks

To compile the benchmarks, follow the instructions in each 
benchmark's README file. 


-- SimpleScalar

It is possible to cross-compile the benchmarks for SimpleScalar, however this
feature has not been actively maintained. The README files for each benchmark
have instructions for cross-compilation.
